good thing about this is nobody reads this...the bad thing is that
...nobody reads this.&nbsp
column3: This journal used to be a

column1: place where I could run...where I could just vent when there was no one
else to vent to.&nbsp
column2: The last time I wrote an entry in this was

column1: exactly 4 months ago right after I graduated high school.. a great end
to a great 4 years followed by a great summer....and the beginning of a
great start to college.&nbsp
venting. I guess thats what happens tho...you get throw into a fabulous
new chaos of life where everything ...and I mean everything is
new.&nbsp
column2: I love it here...the people, the atmosphere, the classes,

column1: the teachers...everything.&nbsp
Im not talking about the two girls hold hands in kindergarden alone and
youre the odd one out, Im talking about the growing up, everyones got a
boyfriend and had sex kind of alone.&nbsp
shouldnt bother me so much because I have some close friends that are
in the same position so in that way Im not alone.&nbsp
people that I spend everyday with those are the ones surrounding me in
sex and boyfriends and best friendships...and Im constantly the odd one
out.&nbsp
column2: Maybe theyre right sometimes...maybe I do it to myself

column1: by&nbsp
column2: putting myself in such a position that i set myself out among

column1: the rest.&nbsp
running across the bathroom to hang out with crazy Jamie and talk about
well...everything...or shes on the phone talking to the boyfriend..what
do I have to connect with? I wish I had better confrontational
skills..like when Liz, Jamie and Meg decided to notify Katie and I
quite matter of factly that theyll be tripling next year...which is
fine whatever but I guess it was awkward.&nbsp
brought up...my mom put me down alot so I learned to just confide in
myself ...and maybe a few other people once in a while.&nbsp
you grow some friends leave...thank god for Jenna...I love having her
close...and Im ecstatic that she came up for the weekend.&nbsp
I threw up friday and was DD saturday but whatever ...she was happy so
I was happy.&nbsp
column2: And Wendy, maybe Ed and the grents are coming Sunday

column1: to take me for dinner...so thatll be nice.&nbsp
column2: I think I just need a

column1: break.&nbsp
Or Matt.&nbsp
column3: Im extremely happy that he got what he

column1: always wanted tho : Japan.&nbsp
much shit we've dealt with.&nbsp
column2: But I still wish hed email me or

column1: something.&nbsp
column2: I always used to get so pissed at him for not having

column1: time to talk for me...but I understand why...he had a gf and
school...college takes up sooo much time.&nbsp
say if) my dad goes down to see him in december he'll take lots of
pictures and things
column2: maybe bring back stuff. My dad deserves a vacation

column1: too.&nbsp
column2: Poor parents...theyre all alone, even Dad said he was

column1: getting lonely and its really quite. Change is hard.
I dont know what it is I want now, or whats wrong really, and why I
cant sit and talk with the people I live with.&nbsp
trouble expressing myself and it sucks.&nbsp
this anyway so its really just random thoughts floating through some
space on teh internet no one will ever read or see...which is good
enough for me.&nbsp
column2: I figure no matter when I write again ....Ill be

column1: single....a virgin...and hopefully still in the PA program.&nbsp
I have friends and family to lean back on.&nbsp
life.
I miss you Grandma, Matt, Mel......so many...

one very important event fell in that time span.&nbsp
the rest of my senior class, am now a GMHS alumni.&nbsp
guys, WE DID IT!!
Graduation was AMAZING, especially since it was actually outside for
the first time in the four years we've all been a part of that high
school...and no faculty could completely keep track of any and all
silly string, confetti, confetti bombs, air horns, beach balls, etc.
which we made <span style=""font-style: italic
when we decorated the courtyard, or the penis once we officially
recieved our diplomas.&nbsp

nice touch...I cant believe how many people asked if he was okay

column1: rocked and I love you!!...same with Ms. Bastiannse and the rest.&nbsp
been through so much together and its been great.&nbsp
the police actually call and say I can get my purse back! :-) oh
Malcolm.

have to say is another month and I'm done

of.....food and ...condiments haha least we had a Navy girl with big

Everyone always laughs about Friday the 13th, joking about the vast
array of unluckiness that overshadows the next 24 hours that you're
forced to face with once thursday's are over.&nbsp
really had any Friday the 13th stories, its always been just another
day, more time just passing by.&nbsp
the same.&nbsp
column2: Friday was the day my Grandpa Tomeck passed away.&nbsp

column1: And of course no matter how close you are or aren't to the individual
whose left you....somewhere inside you you're still filled with this
redundant kind of emptiness.&nbsp
my Grandparents on my mother's side.&nbsp
alzheimers or some form of bad dementia for the later part of his life
so I was gone from all his memories, and it was rather difficult or
seemingly meaningless to visit him because he wouldn't remember
that...actually subtract the meaningless and add difficult.&nbsp
scared, and uncomfortable...those ""old folks homes"" never seemed homey
to me, I could never really understand how a person could be happy
there, but fortunately enough I'm not at that point in my life
yet.&nbsp
column2: But I must admit I do remember a lot of things about my

column1: Grandpa from when I was little, when he was just another Grandpa,
yelling at my Grandma to get him food in the regular ""Marty!"" fashion
and always letting us have whatever we wanted...which was generally the
case with my Grandmother as well.&nbsp
I have fewer memories than I may have liked with my Grandpa, his death
makes me think of my Grandma and her passing away several years
ago.&nbsp
column2: I was there beside my Mom until the end of&nbsp

column1: Grandma actually joked about who weighed more between me and her right
before she <span style=""font-weight: bold
sick.&nbsp
column2: Besides the young memories I have like when my parents

column1: would go on trips and leave my brother and I at my Mom's parents and
theyd feed us til our stomachs we're about to explode,&nbsp
memories right up to when she died which was not long before my cousins
wedding which was another heartbreak...she couldnt be there, though
maybe she was...in spirit.&nbsp
Every time Id go down to Saratoga with my mother and visit my
Grandmother (my Grandpa was in the nursing home) there was always a
point in which some arguement would start ...whether it was about
something important like my Grandmothers health as she gets older or
what were eatting..there was always an arguement.&nbsp
knew when.&nbsp
column2: It was like a script in some crap drama that never

column1: quite made it to the set.&nbsp
column2: Almost like it still needed to be

column1: perfected.&nbsp
column2: But it was, because it made me love them more in some

column1: silly way.&nbsp
column2: Of all the times my Mom and my Grandma have been there

column1: for me throughout my life, that was my chance to be there for them,
both of them.&nbsp
column2: And as much as I hated it, when we were on our way

column1: home, I was never upset about it, it was normal.&nbsp
family.&nbsp
column2: And now that time has passed....

column1: &nbsp
column4: Its funny when you think about it, life is almost

column1: like a story that doesn't seem to exist until it ends because its then
that you really look back and analyze the memories as well as cherish
them
column2: no matter how good nor how bad..there's no limit to a

column1: memory.&nbsp
column2: However, you're writing your life's story every second of

column1: every minute of every hour of each and every single day with the
choices you make and the paths you take....and the obstacles you make
it through.&nbsp
column2: You write it with adventures, with heartaches, with

column1: pictures, with notes, with stupid mistakes...either way its all in
there.&nbsp
column2: It's when an individual passes on that their story truly

column1: presents itself, because it seems that there is now a beginning a
middle and an end and the saga is finally complete.&nbsp
however is not an end except for maybe what we see which is our loved
one walking and talking ...but there is no end to their existance
whatsoever.&nbsp
column2: After death they only exist in a new respect, maybe

column1: even a more pleasant one.&nbsp
column2: Unfortunatly we can never really know

column1: until we get there ourselves.&nbsp
column2: But though it may be hard to reach

column1: a major part of your life and have a loved one not be there, the
mistake is in failing to realize that they are there...theyre there
watching every second and their pride is what gives you strength to
face your fears.&nbsp
column2: Of course this is all my thoughts pouring out as

column1: I go because I just needed to get things out...but its also what I feel
is true.&nbsp
column2: I didn't go out last night after work to end up bawling

column1: on the couch of one of the few true amazing friends I have for
nothing.&nbsp
column2: But it was hard to sit there and enjoy myself...I

column1: couldn't even explain it if I tried.&nbsp
column2: I felt the same emptiness I

column1: felt when other loved ones have passed...maybe in a different way but
it was definitely there, and I wanted to just hug someone and hold on
for hours...though I know thatd get a little old, but I did...I wanted
to fill the pain and emptiness even for a minute. And I did...for a
minute or two, but itd come back..sometimes twice as hard.
&nbsp
column4: People probably think I'm crazy crying about a

column1: Grandpa...but it wasnt just another Grandpa...I was close..and am still
extremely close to my Mom's side of the family...my Dad's side makes me
feel like some unappreciative outcast that they're obligated to
love.&nbsp
column2: Well, at least my Grandparents on that side, my Aunt's and

column1: Uncle's are great...blah
&nbsp
column4: I guess I've babbled enough...no one really reads

column1: this anyway...so its time for me to put food in my system and get
through the day.&nbsp
tomorrow..then who knows. Ambulance ride time tomorrow?
hmmm....great.&nbsp
Ash, Jeff, Dan...thank you so much. : )

column1: Ok so it's actually not quite summer, but I'd say with a couple 80
degree days we're getting pretty damn close.&nbsp
until graduation!!! C.r.a.z.y. Yet soooo exciting.&nbsp
must say with the beautiful weather, how I managed to get freaking
walking pnemonia is beyond me....damn colds that leave me vulnerable
for other crazy things to get into my body and turn my lungs
into....what was Ashley's analogy? Oh right, water balloons lol.&nbsp
It's okay though I suppose I'll let it slide because I'm beating this
freaking thing dammit! ...Let's see I've been some kinda sick for about
two weeks and (over vacation)...so since last Sunday, I've
hung out with the boys, went to Caitlin's to make dirt and watch Mulan
(""Let's kick some HUNNY buns!"") hahaha, umm got sent home from track
Monday so I went shopping with Jen in Avon, then went to see Guess Who?
with Ash and Amanda...haha funny times. Hmm Tuesday...once I was
officially diagnosed at the Dr.'s office, the craziest beach trip <span style=""font-style: italic
began, complete with a trunk full of ...refreshments, lol some rocks, a
bbq, random people lying next to us after we fell asleep on the rocks,
hmm yea fun times. :) Thus I spose it's unecessary to say I went to
track Tuesday either...or yesterday for that matter.&nbsp
on...Wednesday, I went to the neurologist (yes more doctor's) about my
migraine...haha she was great, thick accent, went to medical school in
South Africa...yea, all that good stuff lol...to be told that I was
most likely having rebound headaches from taking ibuprofen everyday
...so I got more drugs to replace that.&nbsp
madre and I completed about 3 more hours worth of errands...came home
and I got some more sun while she ran even more errands.&nbsp
was good tho because we actually managed to run the car on empty so we
could fill it up for cheap.&nbsp
column2: And when I say cheap, I mean

column1: cheap..err. There's no such thing as cheap when it comes to gas anymore
really but oh well it was Wednesday so we got that extra 5 cents off
every gallon or whatever.&nbsp
Thursday...that was my complete and utter lazy Lindsay day.&nbsp
up early...Mom went to Northhampton for the day with friends, Dad went
to work so I slept, watched tv, got mac and cheese mmmmm, slept more
watched more tv....was sleeping til the madre came home even lol and
made her get me Mulan II....which was pretty good but as in most cases,
I preferred the original.&nbsp
complete with the OC, Gone in 60 Seconds and Rush Hour. schweet.&nbsp
Sry babes no going out for me last night.
Then we reached this morning...where I realized not only fuck vacations
almost over!! but I still feel the same dissappointment in myself and
anger towards...well yeah, as I did after it all happened..I hate falling
into the same traps I always do, which is why I can't wait to get out of
here.&nbsp
column2: Some people I really do need to leave behind.

event,"Nothin' bout love is less than confusing
You can win when you're losing, stand when you're falling
I can't figure it out.
Nothin' bout love can make an equation nothin' short of amazing
Wish I could explain it
But I don't know how.
~Leann Rimes
Recently, a friend wrote a big long entry in his xanga about friends
column2: what they are, who they are, what

column1: they mean to a person..etc. And yesterday when I first read it I thought, ""I know all this, I love my
friends to death and are what I value the most."" But then, me being...me learned alot more last night.
I managed to turn a hilarious night full of stupid dancing, beer pong, jello shots, heart to hearts lol

and just plain good times into me fighting and crying about driving home.  All this didnt go without bailing on another friend mind you...(sry! :-/) But yeah, seeing as how I was too retarded (in all senses
of the word) to calm down for two minutes and try to explain what the hell was wrong, I definitely caused
a rather large comotion and, well personally, I woulda been mad at me.  I knew underneath all the whining
and crying and fighting that I couldnt drive, and Nick was right when he said Id thank him after...I truly
do appreciate that they cared enough to literally fight me on it.  But Im not sure I  even wanted to
drive, mostly I knew I just HAD to get home and soon. And about 90% of myself was mad and upset that I lost
so much control of the situation. I was a complete moron and for that I reaaallly want to call out of work

today so that I dont have to face people.  Yeah Im a chicken like that. And I hate it.  So yeah about friends, I really wouldnt be anywhere without them, I mean I was drinking like 5 seconds down the road and
I couldnt even freakin stay straight enough to drive that far home. Thank god for people that take keys.
I love you all really I do even if Im dumb.  I love that I can feel completely safe with my friends and
completely comfortable with myself when Im around them... even when Im silly and random and probably
stupidly embarrassing to be around.  Thats what makes life living for...not the food, not the successes in
money and jobs, though those help you build confidence and be proud and they are a major element, not the
dating relationships except for those where youre boyfriend/girlfriend is youre best friend, but the
relationships with friends ..they truly mean the world to me, and probably most people.
Its crazy what we put people through to kind of subconsciously prove their friendship to us and visa versa.
You dont mean to make them fight you for youre own safety, but they do because they love you and they
care about you and if they didnt they wouldnt truly be a good friend because they didnt look out for you.
Which is rather twisted because when youre caught up in something you just want things to happen the way
you want them to and when they dont you get angry, but youre not really angry at anyone...mostly youre just
angry with yourself for being so stupidly naive.  Its a crazy world but weve all been there and were still
growing up and pushing ourselves to be that perfect person and through it all we'll constantly make our

mistakes and learn from them...some more than once.  But we'll always have someone there whose ballsy (sp?) enough to tell us we're being idiots and we'd do the same for them...and then when its all over hug them
and tell them that its okay.  And thats the best part, the forgiveness and leeway you have to be yourself.
Thats all for now I think, I love you and I'm sorry, but I definitely had fun and hopefully I didn't
completely ruin anyones night. This weekend has been a wide world of unexpected..friday night dinner and
then suffield wha? lol Ah the people in my life..."

is my tribute to the nice girls. <span style=""font-style: italic
column2: >To the nice girls who are overlooked,

column1: who become friends and nothing more, who spend hours fixating upon
their looks and their personalities and their actions because it must
be they that are doing something wrong. This is for the girls who don't
give it up on the first date, who don't want to play mind games, who
provide a comforting hug and a supportive audience for a story they've
heard a thousand times. This is for the girls who understand that they
aren't perfect and that the guys they're interested in aren't either,
for the girls who flirt and laugh and worry and obsess over the
slightest glance, whisper, touch, because somehow they are able to keep
alive that hope that maybe... maybe this time he'll have understood.
This is an homage to the girls who laugh loud and often, who are
comfortable in skirts and sweats and combat boots, who care more than
they should for guys who don't deserve their attention. This is for
those girls who have been in the trenches, who have watched other girls
time and time again fake up and make up and fuck up the guys in their
lives without saying a word. This is for the girls who have been there
from the beginning and have heard the trite words of advice, from
there are plenty of fish in the sea,"" to ""time heals all wounds."" This
is to honor those girls who know that guys are just as scared as they
are, who know that they deserve better, who are seeking to find it.
<br style=""color: rgb(204, 102, 204)
<span style=""color: rgb(204, 102, 204)
is for the girls who have never been in love, but know that it's an
experience that they don't want to miss out on. For the girls who have
sought a night with friends and been greeted by a night of catcalling,
rude comments and explicit invitations that they'd rather not have
experienced. This is for the girls who have spent their weekends
sitting on the sidelines of a beer pong tournament or a case race, or
playing Florence Nightingale for a vomiting guy friend or a comatose
crush, who have received a drunk phone call just before dawn from
someone who doesn't care enough to invite them over but is still
willing to pass out in their bed. <span style=""font-style: italic
column2: >This is for the girls who have left

understand through a subliminally appealing profile, who have time and
time again dropped their male friend hint after hint after hint only to
watch him chase after the first blonde girl in a skirt. This is for the
girls who have been told that they're too good or too smart or too
pretty, who have been given compliments as a way of breaking off a
relationship, who have ever been told they are only wanted as a friend.
<br style=""color: rgb(204, 102, 204)

who believe the excuses because it's easier to believe that it's not

nights spent dissecting every word and syllable and inflection in his

when you've seen from across the room him leaning a little too close,
or standing a little too near, or talking a little too softly for the

died or his little brother crashed his car and you held him, thinking
that if you only comforted him just right, or said the right words, or
rubbed his back in the right way then perhaps he'd realize what it was
that he already had. This is for the night you realized that it would
never happen, and the sunrise you saw the next morning after failing to
sleep.

<br style=""color: rgb(204, 102, 204)
<span style=""color: rgb(204, 102, 204)
is what I don't understand. Men sit and question and whine that girls
are only attracted to the mean guys, the guys who berate them and
belittle them and don't appreciate them and don't want them
them for sex and think of little else than where their next conquest
will be made. Men complain that they never meet nice girls, girls who
are genuinely interested and compelling, who are intelligent and sweet
and smart and beautiful
column2: men despair that no good women want to share

column1: in their lives, that girls play mindgames, that girls love to keep them
hanging. Yet, men, I ask you: were you to meet one of these genuinely
interested, thrillingly compelling, interesting and intelligent and
sweet and beautiful and smart girls, were you to give her your number
and wait for her to call... and if you were to receive a call from her
the next day and she, in her truthful, loyal, intelligent and
straightforward nice girl fashion, were to tell you that she finds you
intriguing and attractive and interesting and worth her time and
perhaps material from which she could fashion a boyfriend, would you or
would you not immediately call your friends to tell them of the
stalker chick"" you'd met the night prior, who called you and wore her
heart on her sleeve and told the truth? And would you, or would you
not, refuse to make plans with her, speak with her, see her again, and
once again return to the bar or club or party scene and search once
more for this ""nice girl"" who you just cannot seem to find? Because
therein lies the truth, guys: we nice girls are everywhere. But you're
not looking for a nice girl. You're not looking for someone genuinely
interested in your intermural basketball game, or your anatomy midterm
grade, or that argument you keep having with your father
looking for a quick fix, a night when you can pretend to have a
connection with another human being which is just as disposable as the
condom you were using during it.
<br style=""color: rgb(204, 102, 204)
<span style=""color: rgb(204, 102, 204)
lookout for nice girls, guys, when you pass us up on every step you
take. Sometimes we go undercover
sometimes when that girl in the low cut shirt or the too tight
miniskirt won't answer your catcalls, sometimes you're looking at a
nice girl in whore's clothing - - we might say we like the attention,
we might blush and giggle and turn back to our friends, but we're all
thinking the same thing: ""This isn't me. Tomorrow morning, I'll be
wearing a teeshirt and flannel shorts, I'll have slept alone and I'll
be making my hungover best friend breakfast. See through the disguise.
See me."" You never do. Why? Because you only see the exterior, you only
see the slutty girl who welcomes those advances. You don't want the
nice girl.. so don't say you're looking for a relationship:
relationships take time and energy and intent, three things we're
willing to extend - - but in return, we're looking for compassion and
loyalty and trust, three things you never seem willing to express.
Maybe nice guys finish last, but in the race they're running they're
chasing after the whores and the sluts and the easy-targets... the nice
girls are waiting at the finish line with water and towels and a
congradulatory hug (and yes, if she's a nice girl and she likes you,
the sweatiness probably won't matter), hoping against hope that maybe
you'll realize that they're the ones that you want at the end of that
silly race.
<br style=""color: rgb(204, 102, 204)
<span style=""color: rgb(204, 102, 204)
column2: >So maybe it won't last forever. Maybe some of those

happens, we still have each other, that silly race to watch, and all
the chocolate we can eat (because what's a concession stand at a race
without some chocolate?)"

column4: It kinda pinched a gut somewhere because yeah its easy and in a way..natural for teenagers to lie to their parents...to an extent.&nbsp

column7: And directly after the worst of it was over I didnt even start making better decisions...in fact I did the same thing with the same naivity.&nbsp
